Named after Lieutenant General Leslie James Morshead

Leslie Morshead won fame as the defender of Tobruk during the Second World War and is among the most renowned Australian divisional commanders of that war. He was born at Ballarat in Victoria on 18 September 1889 and became a teacher. Joining the AIF in September 1914 as a lieutenant, Morshead was posted to the 2nd Battalion. 

By the time he landed at Gallipoli on 25 April 1915 he was a captain; by August, when he fought at Lone Pine, he had been promoted to major. After Gallipoli he was promoted to lieutenant colonel and given command of the 33rd Battalion, which arrived in France in November 1916. Morshead led the battalion successfully through Messines and the Passchendaele campaign of late-1917, was awarded the Distinguished Service Order, and continued to command through the battles Villers-Bretonneux and Amiens in 1918. 

Morshead joined General Monash's staff for the demobilisation of the AIF and returned to Sydney in December 1919. He married Myrtle Woodside in November 1921. Having failed to make a success of a soldier-settlers' block in Queensland, Morshead returned to Sydney to work in shipping, gaining promotions and posts in several Australian cities and in England. 

He remained active in the militia, commanding two battalions and reaching the rank of temporary brigadier. In October 1939 he was given command of the 18th Brigade, sailing for Britain in May 1940. The following February Morshead was promoted to major general in command of the 9th Division, then in the Middle East. Reputed to be a tough commander who could be blunt with senior officers, Morshead led his division through the siege of Tobruk where his aggressive defence denied the Germans a breakthrough but earned him the ire of some subordinates concerned at the level of losses. 

His success at Tobruk was followed by promotion to lieutenant general and command of the AIF in the Middle East. Morshead, at the risk of alienating his British superiors, argued to keep the 9th Division together in the face of British demands to detach individual brigades. He led the division through the battle of El Alamein, where the 9th Division's contribution was considered vital to the victory. During the battle, he regularly visited both the front and the wounded behind the lines. 

Returning to Australia in 1943, Morshead took command of II Corps in October and then in November was elevated to command both New Guinea Force and the Second Australian Army. In May 1944 he was given command of I Corps, leading them through the final battles of the war in Borneo. After the war, he chaired a military court of enquiry into Major General Bennett's departure from Singapore in February 1942. 

Morshead refused offers of military and diplomatic posts, as well as the governorship of Queensland, returning instead to the shipping industry as manager of the New South Wales branch of the Orient Line; later he became its Australian general manager. He held a number of other directorships and civil appointments and was involved in right-wing politics before becoming ill with cancer in the mid-1950s. Morshead died in Sydney on 26 September 1959.

Place Name: A R And F Ditterich Reserve
Historical Information:
Arthur Ralph Ditterich was a Shire of Flinders Councillor from 1961-1964.
A.R. & F. Ditterich are Life Members of the Main Ridge Cricket Club - Ralph and Frank Ditterich were keen cricketers and involved in community affairs. They were involved in the planning and building of the bowls club and other works associated with the grounds. Both had orchards and lived in Valley View Lane, Main Ridge.  Prior to 1926 Main Ridge was known as Main Creek and the name change was brought about by Frank Ditterich.  Seven acres (2.8 hectares) was bought from C. Rigby in 1932 for a recreation ground at Main Ridge for the sum of 50 pounds ($100). A 10 pound ($20) deposit was raised by the community funded in part by a 'sheep guessing competition'. The balance payable over 5 years was raised by community fundraising efforts.
In 1957 the gates were given as a gift by Mrs Lillian Adams of Main Ridge.
On 28th April 1959 the Shire President was invited to unveil a plaque in memory of Frank Ditterich.  Frank was born in Long Gully, Bendigo on 17th September 1895 and died on 28th December 1956 at Mentone. He married his wife Jessie in 1930. They had two sons Richard and David.
Ralph was born in St Arnaud on 4th July, 1893 and married his wife Margaret in Palmerston, New Zealand in 1926. Their son Allan was born in 1929 and died in 1947. Ralph died in Redcliffe, Queensland in 1974.

The council purchased Alexandra Park for Ã¿Â£200 ($400) in 1896. This became the Mornington Football Club's home ground, and it is now home to Mornington Football Netball & Cricket Clubs. The Mornington Cricket Club was established in 1863.  By 1905 the reserve was fenced and charges were made for entry, half the proceeds going towards improvements.  It was listed among the civic assets by Cr F. Linley in his submission to the Railway Commissioners, noting then that money was being spent on football and cricket at the reserve. A further two acres (.8 hectare) were acquired there in 1948. 
Possibly named in honour of Queen Alexandra, mother of King George V who reigned between 1910-1936, and after who King Georges Ave in Mornington was named.

B.A. Cairns Reserve was developed in the 1880s as a sports venue for cricket and football, but was also used for gymkhanas and stock auctions.  In the 1970s it was named after Bertie Alexander Cairns (1895-1979), a member of the pioneering Cairns family, in acknowledgment of his tireless dedication to the care and maintenance of the sporting reserve.
Bert did so much valued service, especially for the Park and Cricket Club. He was also a very good golfer. As a General Carrier for many years, he transported fish and other produce to the markets and brought goods back for the farmers and residents.
He is buried with his wife in the Flinders Cemetery.

The Barbers were one of Somerville's early well-known nursery families.
In the mid-1800s, Claude Barber settled on a property in Lower Somerville Road. He then bought a 60-acre (24 hectare) property in Eramosa Road which was the first property on the Mornington Peninsula with the name of "Western Port". The original drive into the homestead was located in the area of today's Jordan Street. Barber Reserve is part of a former paddock on the farm property.  The orchard covered approximately 40 acres (16 hectares).

The Maw family donated the land to Council in 1964 and was proposed as one of 3 names for the reserve.

The reserve was named after Benbenjie who was of the Boon wurrung tribe which lived in the Wonga (McCrae) area during the McCrae's occupation and he is said to have taught the McCrae children how to hunt and fish.

Benjamin John Benton, born in Essex, England, brought his family to Australia aboard the "Elizabeth", arriving in the Mornington area in about 1851.  He was one of the trustees responsible for the acquisition of Ã¿Â½ acre of land in Moorooduc on which to build the first school and church.
He died in 1914 and is buried at Mornington Cemetery.

Historical Information: On Friday 7 December, 1951, a 49-year-old housewife named Mrs. Elsie Dorrington became the Shire of Mornington's first woman Councillor, when six hundred ratepayers decided to break with tradition of no women in the Shire Council. Cr. Dorringtons' first job was to urge the Council to set up a home-help scheme and she also went on to initiate a number of social welfare schemes in the Shire. Mrs Dorrington served three terms as Councillor until 1958. In 1960 Mrs Dorrington was appointed as Victorian Justice of the Peace and sat on the bench at Mornington's Magistrates Court. From 1961 to 1969, Mrs Dorrington worked for the Department of Mental Hygiene as the Manager of Moorakyne Girls Hostel in Hawthorn. Elsie Dorrington passed away on 1 June, 1995 in Mount Eliza.

Named after James Ford who held a pastoral lease at Point Nepean in the early 1840s where he raised horses, wheat and other farm produce for ships and the quarantine station. It is understood that he named the village 'Portsea' and established the first baths and hotel in the area.  Ford was also owner of the land which comprises the newly created subdivision that includes the reserve.

Joseph Harris arrived from England in 1856 and initially made his name as a nurseryman. In the late 1800's he acquired the site of the Scout Camp, with an early emphasis on the planting of exotic species. On his death in 1925 the family gave the land to the Boy Scouts Association and in 1932 the Governor and Chief Scout of Victoria, Lord  Somers, officially opened the Scout Camp.

This reserve is named in honour of two of Dromana's pioneering families: the Shaw family and the McKeown family.

The Shaw family (Benjamin and Elizabeth) arrived in Dromana in 1875 and established Kangerong Guest House. Their son Archibald Shaw married Maud McKeown, daughter of James and Catherine McKeown, and started the family connection. Archibald was elected President of the Flinders Shire Council in 1924. Archibald and Maud raised and educated five children in Dromana (Maurice, Ernest, Archibald, Elizabeth and John). Maurice was the long-term proprietor of the Shell Service Station in Dromana and Shaw's Motors on Nepean Highway for many years prior to his death in 1991 aged 87.

The McKeown family (James and Catherine) arrived in Dromana in 1864. James cut timber for the Dromana pier in 1874 and in 1889 bought Gracefield and land to the East, where they planted an apple orchard. That land covered the area on which the reserve is now located. From 1889 to 1891 they were caretakers at Heronswood and in 1892 the McKeowns built Aringa Guest House (Cnr of Clarendon and Foote Streets Dromana) which was managed by their daughters for over 70 years until after the Second World War. James and Catherine raised 12 children (five sons and seven daughters); one daughter, Edith, the source for the naming of Edith Place, died in Dromana in 1987 aged 100. Two further generations of the Shaw and McKeown families have since lived in Dromana.

The surrounding land and the land on which the reserve is located was subdivided by the descendants of the pioneering Shaws and McKeowns in 1977 and the reserve was transferred to the Shire of Flinders (and since Mornington Peninsula Shire) for use as public open space.

Sydney Alfred Baker (1896-1965) was a Shire of Flinders Councillor (1984-65) who supported early efforts to make provision for public open space and access in subdivision of the Cain's Estate.  The naming proposal was first made by Mr J.G. Ritchie and supported by the Shire of Flinders.

Previously called Checkingurk (or Tichingorouk) and settled by Captain James Reid in 1840, 'The Briars' had a long association with the Balcombe family.  The name was given to a number of Balcombe properties in Australia, all borrowing from a homestead in the hills above the Jamestown, capital of St Helena, an island in the Atlantic Ocean operated under charter by the East India Company. 'In 1837 Captain William Lonsdale chose a larger area than that referred to in the request as a station for a Native Police Corps.  Lonsdale referred to the location of the location of the station as 'on the Dangy-nong Creek at Nerre Nerre Warrene'.  Neither of these forms of spelling survived.  The Native Police were disbanded in 1851 and the area was then used as a stun depot for Police horses.  The depot acquired its first horses in 1856.'  'Available evidence suggests that the name 'Dandenong Police Paddocks' gradually superseded the older locality name 'Nerre Nerre Warrene' after the establishment of the stud depot.'

Dexters Bush is named after Paul & Elizabeth Dexter in recognition of their efforts and the considerable time in nurturing and maintaining the bushland at the rear of their property in Dickasons Road Heathmont.
The Dexters purchased 5 acres of bushland, running from Dickasons Road to the Dandenong Creek in 1956. They gifted part of the land to Victoria Conservation Trust in 1988 and continued to be actively involved in preserving the bushland through their role on the committee of management, by assisting with plans, strategies and policies to promote the regeneration of the indigenous flora that was present in the soil and other significant species.   The Dexters stepped back from their role in the management of the bushland in 2015 and the land was transferred to Maroondah Council on 23 January 2018. The community and Council have always recognised the bushland as Dexters Bush.

Community consultation to name the park occurred in 2014. The name Barclay was suggested by the Greensborough Historical Society as an option. Their records indicate that in the 1940's this part of Greensborough comprised 5 to 10 acre farmlets, one of which was home to the Barclay family. Henry Barwell Barclay, his wife Dorothy and their six month old son Eric moved to a 10 acre holding at Grace Park, at the end of Henry Street where it intersects with Elder Street, Greensborough in 1938. This farmlet stood where Gladman Street in now located (approximately 350 m south of McKenzie Court). Henry Barclay worked locally, in the market garden at nearby Yallambie House, a mansion on large acreage that fronted the Plenty River, and the produce merchant Stubley's in Greensborough, where he loaded wheat. Henry Barclay died in November 1959.

Yarra Ranges National Park. Named after Cumberland Creek (2). Established 1923 (Forests Commission tourist reserve) and 1929; the word Memorial was added to the name in 1994. Leadbeater's possum was rediscovered in the area in 1961.

Ralph Goode enlisted on 16 August 1914, the first man from Lilydale to do so. He was allotted to the 2nd Field Ambulance to serve as a stretcher bearer and he travelled on the SS Wiltshire in the first convoy to Egypt. He was stationed there until he moved to Lemnos Island and then was at the landing at Gallipoli. He saw service at Anzac Cove and Cape Helles and was there at the Battle of Lone Pine. He was Mentioned in Despatches for his work here. After the evacuation, he was sent back to Egypt where his unit was re-organised and then moved to France.
Between 1916 and 1918 he served on the Western Front, experiencing all the horrors and heroism of those campaigns. He was a veteran of Pozieres, Bullecourt, Passchendaele, Ypres and Delville Wood. In 1918 he returned home to Lilydale, married, had a family and took up a business running a drapers store in Lilydale's Main Street. He also did community work and achieved an extraordinary amount for that township. His family believed his way of coping with what he saw during the war years was to keep himself busy with community work. He was awarded the MBE for his efforts for that community. He died in 1961.

Wattle Park is the only Australian example of a comprehensively developed pleasure park established, owned and operated by a transport authority with the dual aim of promoting its transport services and providing a recreational facility for the public. The layout of the park and its buildings and structures remain intact in their original 1920s form. The name and theme of the park reflect the strong national fervour of the early decades of the century - the wattle is Australia's national floral emblem. It has a historical association with two prominent Melbourne identities, Orland Fenwick, a former lord mayor and Eliza Welch, widow of the co-founder of the retailing firm Ball & Welch, before it was purchased by the Hawthorn Tramways Trust.
The Wurundjeri are the Traditional Owners of the land. The activities of the Wurundjeri people were given exposure through education programs and activities celebrating NAIDOC in 1988.

Ashburton is thought to be named after the ship Lord Ashburton, which arrived in Australia from Great Britain in 1850. Hawthorn and designed many civic, commercial and Heritage Registered houses in Victoria. Jack O'Toole was a policeman, a world champion wood chopper and a well known sports presenter on TV.  The O'Toole family lived next door to the reserve, which been known locally as O'Toole's Paddock.

The late Jack O'Toole was a world champion wood chopper. He won every wood cutting championship in the world including the titles for every Australian state, the Australian, New Zealand, Canadian, American and world titles. He was standing and underhand wood chop world champion for an unparalleled 24 years. Jack O'Toole was also well known for his segment on the Channel 7 World of Sports show for many years. During his time as world champion and also on the World of Sport, he used the site for preparing wood for the World of Sport shows and for the championships. The O'Tooles have resided next door to the site since 1949. Jack O'Toole was a policeman for 30 years during which time he was posted at Kew for a number of those years.

Named for Dr Aubrey Moss, who was very active in both the Medical and local areas. Dr Moss represented his peers on numerous Committees and Boards, as well as continuing his private practice.

Named after Desmond 'Des' Ignatius Custerson, a well known Dandenong identity and, with his wife Maureen, started the Chubbies Dance Band. They remained the core members of the band for 50 years. The Chubbies Dance Band played at the old Workingman's Club in Dandenong and was the first band to play there when it was renovated. The band was the heart and soul of the well-known Lyndale Dance and raised funds for the Dandenong and District Hospital for 28 years. The band also played at dances all over Victoria to raise funds for charities such as the Make-A-Wish Foundation, Yooralla, the Helicopter Search & Rescue Service and local churches and communities. Des played the last gig with the Chubbies Dance Band at aged 84. Des also had a long association with the St Mary's Parish Football Club (he coached the Midgets for almost 15 years) and the Dandenong Football Club, through his son Neil. Des and Maureen lived in Sunset Grove, Dandenong for over 25 years with their five children. They were well known and respected in the local community. Des and Maureen embraced the diversity of Dandenong and always welcomed new migrants to the area. He was a gentle and ethical man that shared his love of Dandenong and football with his neighbours. Des passed away in April 2016.

Named after Geoffrey Carson who was a long-time local resident actively associated with numerous school, sport and other local community organisations.  In particular in 1998, he successfully campaigned for the renewal of playground equipment in the reserve.

The Orchardists were seeking a connecting road from Springvale Road and Old Warrandyte Road to Doncaster Road and one of them asked the Councillor whether the residents would be getting their new road and the Councillor, having in mind an even vote requiring a casting vote by the President replied 'It will depend on the way the cat jumps'.

Originally called Burial Hill, this rise at the western end of the city grid was renamed when the flagstaff was erected in September 1840 for signalling shipping activities in Hobsons Bay. George Gordon McCrae reminisced that 'Bunting and great wicker balls' told what type of vessel was approaching and the port of origin. Marryat's code of signal flags was used to carry news from Williamstown. The advent of the telegraph rendered the flagstaff redundant and operation ceased on 1 October 1857. The signaller's store and dwelling were incorporated into the Flagstaff Observatory. At 130 ft (39.6 m) in height, and with better sight lines of Williams-town and the bay, Flagstaff Hill had been preferred to Batmans Hill as the observatory site. The Flagstaff Gardens were planted on the site in the 1860s.

This name was recorded by A. W. Howitt, anthropologist, from conversations from sometime between 1897 and 1901 with William Barak, ngurungaeta (leader) of the Wurundjeri-willam, the traditional owners of what is now northern Melbourne, and Dick Richards, Barak's fellow Kulin countryman. The Kulin was an alliance of Aboriginal nations in central Victoria. Howitt jotted down Aboriginal names, mostly in the Woiwurrung language once spoken in the Melbourne area, corresponding to landmarks and municipalities that arose in Melbourne town during Barak's lifetime (c.1824 to 1903).

Named after Caroline Chisholm (1808-1877). Caroline Chisholm worked tirelessly for female immigrants in NSW, as it was her belief that the best influences on colonial life were marriage and family life. She had continued this work on her return to England, and had encouraged poor people, especially young women, to leave the squalor of their homeland and emigrate to Australia. Her work in Victoria was in providing clean, cheap and safe accommodation to families or single people on the way to the Mount Alexander diggings. She pressured the government into a scheme to built ten shelter sheds, which would provide accommodation for single men, single women and families. While none of the sheds lasted, the park is in the rough area where the sheds were located.

Jack has, appropriately, had the extended clubrooms (originally built in 1978) named in his honour for his contribution to the club. The reserve was renamed in honour of Harold's contribution to the club.

Keys Rd ground was an old rubbish tip that had been filled and covered in a layer of soil. The surface was continually subsiding, in 1965 junior cricket was played on this ground and the oval was found unsuitable for cricket; it was actually a muddy paddock in winter and a corrugated concrete oval in summer. Cricket never returned to this oval.
Harold could see the potential in the Keys Rd Reserve and in 1967 donated the cost of a single car steel garage placed on a concrete slab, which was to become our first changing room/clubroom, and was later known as "the old tin shed". It had the nickname of "Mr. Cat's Cottage" on a sign above the door.
The following year a small extension was added that held a briquette hot water service and several showers.
As the Club grew over the years, Harold continued to be a committee member and also continued to liaise with Council regarding club matters. Whether it was gaining approval for further extensions to the shed (there were several extensions over the years), ground improvements, a second playing field, flood lighting and eventually Clubrooms were built in 1978.
Harold was the "go to person" in regard to Council. He developed a very good relationship with Mayor Bricker, who later became our Patron for many years and over time became one of the Rams strongest supporters.
Gaining significant funding for a sport that was practically unknown in the district, was not easy. The relationship between Harold and Cr. Bricker proved vital on several occasions as the councillor supported funding for the club which otherwise might not have been approved.
That the Rams are based at Keys Road can be put down to Harold's dedication to securing a permanent home for rugby union in Moorabbin.

The club's playing jersey is also a legacy from Harold Caterson's U18 Marlins team.
He was President in 1968 and 1971; Vice President in 1969, 1970 and from 1972 to 1981 inclusive. Ordinary Committee Member 1965 to 1967.
Harold was made a Life Member in 1977.
Additionally, he was the Moorabbin club delegate to the Victorian Rugby Union for many years; and he would collate the results and statistics for the VRU weekly magazine each week during the season.
His work with the club, Council and the VRU continued right up to his sudden death in 1981.
It is worth noting that four generations of the Caterson family have been involved in playing and administrating the Moorabbin Rugby Club since its inception in 1965.

The Sir Zelman Cowen Park is located at 458 Glenferrie Road, Kooyong opposite the Kooyong Lawn Tennis Club and is named in honour of the former (and now deceased) Governor - General who was a resident of the City of Stonnington in his retirement who enjoyed long walks in Council's parks with his wife. The land that comprises Kooyong Park is owned by Council after the Malvern Council purchased the land in 1925-1926. Our research has found that the name of the Park is first raised in Council annual reports in 1931-32 when the curator reported he had planted trees there during the year. Apart from his residency of Stonnington it is noted that Sir Zelman Cowen also had national and international credentials and achievements.

'This park overlooks a historic road intersection.  During the 19th century travellers to the northern goldfields often took the route up to Mt. Alexander Road, along the Bulla or Deep Creek Road (Now Melrose Drive), and turning right here down Broadmeadows Road (now Mickleham Road) to join what was the old Sydney Road.  The Junction Hotel, on the opposite north-western corner was a popular overnight stopover and this park would have seen many travellers tents.  By the start of the 20th century this park was part of the Camp Hill property owned by the Gilligan brothers.'

Historical Information: ''The Hayes Reserve' after early pioneers of this area.  Mark Hayes selected the land at Tooborac in August 1857 and the family lived in tenets on a little creek on the east side of the road (which is now the reserve in question) until the stone house 'Leicester House' was built.  This was finished and occupied by 1862.  The House was continuously lived in by members of the Hayes family, until the property was sold in the 1970's.  The ship Mark and his family arrived in Australia aboard was the 'Harry Lorrequest', which sailed from Plymouth 27th November, 1850.  It arrived in Port Phillip on 14th March, 1851.'
